Only this afternoon, dear Consul Le Maistre, I became aware, that a French Warship was here, otherwise I would have paid my respects earlier to the Admiral and Officers at your Consular Office at once;
Dubourdieu, a French naval cruiser of 3,300 tons and 21 guns arrived at Melbourne on 16 March 1892. Its officers included Rear Admiral Emile Parrayon and Capt. Besson. See Argus, 18 March 1892, p. 4. and now even I can only do so by letter, as I am not at all well, and thus obliged to keep within my room. I beg however to send for the kind acceptance of the Admiral and the Captain each a book,
Books not identified. which may be worthy of their acceptance and may prove useful during their voyages occasionally for reference.
